AGI -&nbsp; Foreign Minister Antonio Tajani manifested solidarity for the "horrible images" of the video of the arrest in Miami of the Italian student Matteo Falcinelli. Tajani made it during a long call to the boy's mother. Tajani has also promised that the "government will do everything to ensure Matthew to conclude his studies in Florida and have justice". The head of the Farnesina called directly the mother of Falcinelli, Vlasta Studenicova, who is located in Miami, and kept on the phone with her for about twenty minutes. The woman thanked the minister for his interest. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;"I offered the lady and family of Falcinelli my warmest solidarity, and above all I have confirmed that the Consulate of Italy in Miami and the whole Farnesina will continue to follow the judicial case and offer assistance to Mr Falcinelli", said Tajani according to the reports of the Farnesina. The minister confirmed to the Falcinelli family that "the Italian Government fulfils its obligation when it defends with its consular structures Italian citizens who require assistance in cases such as those of violent and brutal arrests or detentions". "I was deeply impressed by the violence and the type of treatment that was applied to our young fellow countryman: that system in Italy evokes something that I don't even want to name. With balance and respect for US institutions, but with all the necessary strength, the Farnesina will follow the case of Mr. Falcinelli".
&nbsp;
Matteo Falcinelli was arrested by the Miami police and encapsulated in cell for 13 minutes. The young, originally from Spoleto was in the United States to attend a master's degree at the Florida International University. The arrest and scenes of violence were resumed by the bodycam worn by the agents, that the American lawyer of Falcinelli managed to obtain from the prosecutor only on April 12 in the context of the process, in fact finished with the admission to the PTI (Pre trail intervention), a sort of educational program.
<div </div
&nbsp;
The video is <a href="https://www.quotidiano.net/cronaca/stop-choc-a-miami-studente-italiano-incaprettato-l00po85k?utm_source=dlvr.it&amp;utm_medium=twitter"> was published exclusively by the National Daily. Now the family wants to press formal complaints for abuses, statements not corresponding to the truth and made under oath, illegitimate arrest and tortures suffered by the young man and appeal to the Fourth Amendment. The story begins the night between 24 and 25 February last when the student was arrested during a night intervention in a club.
As the facts have gone, it will be a matter of investigation. According to a first reconstruction, Matteo had had a drink with a girl > and then he realized that his two cell phones had disappeared. On the way out there was already a police patrol waiting for him. The police will write that they have intervened because the boy has created problems in the club so much as to be thrown out> and to have opposed the arrest, making resistance.
"It is at that point that Falcinelli ends on the ground with his hands behind the back and knee of the policeman to press on his neck.> Shortly after the same pictures refer to the arrival of one of the bouncers reporting the two cell phones to the agents" reads on Qn. Then "Falcinelli is taken to the police station. That's where torture happens. A policeman's body cam shows the student inside a cell with stained glass.> Matteo is thrown to the ground, with a strap tie his ankles, tighten his cuffs with the keys and connect the strap strictly to the hands. They pull it hard and then leave it on one side but the boy ends up belly on the ground while the agents close the cell. During the day he was taken to prison, first to the hospital." They were college friends paying bail to release him and warn Matthew's mother.&nbsp;
<h2>Tajani calls attention to the US embassy
On the case of the young Italian arrested in Miami on the night between 24 and 25 February and "subject to a particularly violent detention treatment", Foreign Minister Antonio Tajani> urges the attention of the US authorities.<br> As a note from the Farnesina informs, "from the beginning of the story the Consulate General of Italy in Miami is following the case. At the time of the arrest Mr Falcinelli was subjected to a particularly violent detention treatment, testified by the same body-cams of the police officers who made the stop".<br> "For this reason, in addition to following the case and providing assistance to the family for the legal aspects, the general consul in Miami has emphasized with the local authorities the unacceptable treatment that the young person has suffered. In Rome, the Minister of Foreign Affairs Antonio Tajani has already made the utmost attention to the case of the US ambassador in Italy Jack Markell, recalling that the Italian Government has strictly followed any case of detention of Italian citizens abroad," he reads in the note.
"Falcinelli - the note of the Farnesina continues - had been arrested at the exit of a disco. Miami police had challenged him several crimes, including non-violent resistance to official audiences. It was released two days after the arrest.> The General Consulate in Miami immediately activated: in addition to intervening with the local authorities, he provided the necessary assistance to the compatriot and family members, also providing contacts of the legal office, then chosen by the family". "The General Consulate, in agreement with the Farnesina, will continue to assist the compatriot, keeping close contact with the family," concludes the note.
<h2 The mother: "His life destroyed, we will battle"</h2>
"The actions of the police have re-evoked in me the tortures that the Gestapo carried out during the Second World War > to prisoners and I will go all the way to obtain justice": Vlasta Studenicova, the mother of the Umbrian student Matteo Falcinelli who in a video is encaptured by American policemen for 13 minutes during the arrest in February in Miami, in an interview with the National Daily. "What my son has suffered will never have to happen to any other person in the world, much less to a young man of 25 years, university student abroad," added the woman, born in Slovakia but with Italian citizenship, divorced by a man of Spoleto.<br> "To Matteo, solar boy, enterprising and full of life have removed the smile and destroyed the dreams bringing him even to try to remove his life," said the mother. He was not in the United States when his son was arrested and subjected to unspeakable violence, but now he is in Miami to assist him on campus with his other son Marco.> At the end of March the judge dropped the charges against the Italian student for violence-free resistance to public officials after reporting a bar in which he would create problems (but managers have withdrawn the complaint for violation of private property) in exchange for participation in an educational program.<br> "It's bad, very bad", he reported, "they destroyed his life. He is followed by psychologists and psychiatrists. Initially he was admitted to a hospital > due to the serious injuries he had reported. He was later transferred to a psychiatric hospital because he was at risk of suicide because of the brutal tortures he was inflicted tried to take his life several times. Even now the night dreams of the arrival of the police that tortures him and wakes up screaming. I have to watch him day and night." &nbsp;
<h2 The lawyer, "we will address the prosecutor of Rome"></h2>
The lawyer Francesco Maresca, who assists Matteo Falcinelli and his family, announces that he will address the prosecutor of Rome in the next few hours "to urge her to take care of the case and, in turn, invite the colleagues of Florida and Miami to open an investigation file. We will try to pull the line even with the Farnesina - says to the AGI - and to urge all the appropriate official initiatives". The criminal reports that Matthew's mother and brother are with the boy in Miami.&nbsp;
"I don't know if in the United States the maneuver with which Matthew was arrested is allowed in certain cases but is undoubtedly meaningless considering that it happens 'to fredò in barracks, at a time after the arrest and not in the immediateness of the facts, in the local. I personally defended several police and police officers - Maresca explains - but these modes I have never seen them, even at the last stage". &nbsp;
&nbsp;

